////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
// Acid Test: Declarations with Environment Bodies
//
// A ForSome (or Let) whose body is an environment rather than a single
// expression, e.g.
//
//     n in A for some n in NN     parses as     [n , { (∈ n A) (∈ n ℕ) }]
//
// In the Rule below the ForSome conclusion is the maximal Weeny (it alone
// carries both metavariables A and n; the premise carries only A). Before
// declarations with environment bodies were flagged by forbiddenWeeny, the
// Weeny loop tried to match that declaration first, reached the case in
// matchPropositions that hands the two bodies to the (expression-only) Matching
// package, threw, and was swallowed silently - so the Rule never fired and the
// conclusion did not validate. With environment-bodied declarations flagged as
// forbidden Weenies, the declaration is instantiated as a side effect of
// matching the premise, and the conclusion validates as it should.

➤ "ForSome with an environment body: n in A for some n in NN"
{
  Declare is, nonempty, in
  Rule: :{ If A is nonempty   n in A for some n in NN }
  Assume W is nonempty
  w in W for some w in NN
} ✔︎
